multivariate Cox hazard ratios for channel count and log mutation
count at different channel granularities. Channel count is
significant from 2 through 8 channels, peaks at 3, and collapses
at 10. All three datasets replicate this pattern.}
\label{tab:sensitivity}
\medskip
\begin{tabular*}{\textwidth}{@{\extracolsep{\fill}}rcccc@{}}
\toprule
Channels & Ch HR & Ch $p$ & Mut HR & Mut $p$ \\
\midrule
2 & 1.25 & $2 \times 10^{-52}$ & 0.94 & $4 \times 10^{-9}$ \\
3 & 1.30 & $3 \times 10^{-124}$ & 0.86 & $8 \times 10^{-41}$ \\
4 & 1.21 & $3 \times 10^{-75}$ & 0.88 & $9 \times 10^{-27}$ \\
5 & 1.17 & $8 \times 10^{-58}$ & 0.88 & $6 \times 10^{-22}$ \\
6 & 1.14 & $1 \times 10^{-44}$ & 0.90 & $2 \times 10^{-16}$ \\
7 & 1.10 & $7 \times 10^{-24}$ & 0.93 & $1 \times 10^{-7}$ \\
8 & 1.07 & $3 \times 10^{-14}$ & 0.95 & $4 \times 10^{-4}$ \\
10 & 1.01 & 0.064 & 1.02 & 0.20 \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular*}
\end{table}

The signal is significant at every granularity from 2 to 8 and peaks
at 3~channels ($p = 3 \times 10^{-124}$). At 2~channels, the
grouping is too coarse: both channel count and mutation count are
significant because the two mega-channels still contain meaningful
internal variation. From 3 to 8, channel count absorbs the
predictive power of mutation count, which becomes protective or
non-significant. At 10~channels, over-splitting within
organizational functions makes ``channel count'' collapse back into
a proxy for mutation count.

The peak at 3~channels (genome integrity, growth signaling,
microenvironment) suggests that the coarsest biologically meaningful
grouping captures most of the signal. The specific number of
channels is less important than the principle: grouping mutations by
organizational function outpredicts counting them, and the optimal
granularity is determined by the actual independence structure of
the coupling hierarchy.

\textbf{Cancer-type adjustment.} A natural objection is that channel
count proxies for cancer type: lung cancers have more mutations than
thyroid cancers, and different cancer types have different prognoses.
We tested this by adding cancer type as a covariate (one-hot encoded,
38~types with $n \geq 50$) to the multivariate Cox model. In the
50K cohort, the channel-count hazard ratio barely changes: HR~$= 1.17$
($p = 8 \times 10^{-73}$) vs.\ HR~$= 1.17$ ($p = 1 \times 10^{-88}$)
unadjusted, an attenuation of 1.1\%. MetTropism shows 16\% attenuation
but remains significant ($p = 2 \times 10^{-47}$). MSK-IMPACT 2017
shows no attenuation. Channel count is not a proxy for cancer type.

Stratified analysis within individual cancer types confirms this.
Channel count is significant within non-small cell lung cancer
(HR~$= 1.16$, $p = 3 \times 10^{-13}$), breast cancer
(HR~$= 1.29$, $p = 1 \times 10^{-21}$), prostate cancer
(HR~$= 1.47$, $p = 9 \times 10^{-21}$), and pancreatic cancer
(HR~$= 1.32$, $p = 2 \times 10^{-19}$). Prostate cancer shows
the strongest within-type effect, consistent with its narrow
channel architecture: most prostate tumors are concentrated on a
single coupling axis, so each additional channel severed represents
a larger relative loss of organizational control.

\textbf{Full covariate adjustment.} To test whether channel count
captures anything beyond known prognostic variables, we ran a
kitchen-sink Cox model controlling for every available clinical
attribute simultaneously: tumor mutational burden (TMB), MSI score
and type, cancer type and detailed subtype, age at diagnosis, sex,
tumor purity, fraction genome altered, primary site, sample type,
and gene panel version. In the 50K cohort, this produces 275
covariates. Channel count remains significant: HR~$= 1.09$,
$p = 1 \times 10^{-23}$. MetTropism (187~covariates):
HR~$= 1.11$, $p = 1 \times 10^{-18}$. MSK-IMPACT 2017
(109~covariates): HR~$= 1.14$, $p = 2 \times 10^{-8}$.
After controlling for everything available in three clinical
genomic databases, channel count still predicts survival.

\textbf{Severance hierarchy: cell-intrinsic channels first.}
The six coupling channels are not severed at random. Among patients
with exactly one channel severed ($n = 12{,}558$), 80\% have
PI3K/Growth Signaling or Cell Cycle: the cell-intrinsic channels
that govern proliferation. Endocrine and Immune account for fewer
than 5\%. Among patients with two or more channels severed
($n = 24{,}535$), 98.1\% have at least one cell-intrinsic channel.

The progression ladder is:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{1~channel}: PI3K/Growth (44.5\%) or Cell Cycle
  (35.7\%) dominate. Immune: 0.7\%.
\item \textbf{2~channels}: PI3K/Growth rises to 73.9\%, Cell Cycle
  to 64.6\%. Tissue Architecture enters at 33.6\%.
\item \textbf{3~channels}: PI3K/Growth at 90.8\%, Cell Cycle 80.9\%,
  Tissue Architecture 70.8\%. Endocrine (13.5\%) and Immune (7.2\%)
  remain rare.
\item \textbf{4~channels}: PI3K/Growth at 96.7\%. Endocrine and
  Immune are the last additions (30\%, 25\%).
\end{itemize}

The ordering is PI3K/Growth $\to$ Cell Cycle $\to$ Tissue
Architecture $\to$ DDR $\to$ Endocrine $\to$ Immune. Growth escape
is the gateway; immune evasion is the last system to fall. This is
not a statistical artifact of channel frequency. Cell Cycle is more
common than Tissue Architecture overall, yet at one channel they
have similar representation (35.7\% vs.\ 8.5\%), because the
single-channel patients reflect first hits, not base rates.

This ordering is the escalation chain read in reverse. The channels
severed first (PI3K/Growth, Cell Cycle) are the cell-tissue
boundary: the coupling mechanisms that say ``do not divide without
tissue permission.'' The channels severed last (Endocrine, Immune)
are organism-level controls that operate at levels~2--3 of the
hierarchy. A cell cannot meaningfully escape immune surveillance or
endocrine regulation before it has escaped the basic growth
constraint. The severance hierarchy is the empirical signature of
escalation ordering (Section~\ref{sec:framework}): the first
coupling to break is the lowest level of the chain, and progression
moves upward through the hierarchy as additional channels fall.

The 1.9\% of multi-channel patients who lack a cell-intrinsic
gateway channel are not noise. They are enriched 6.5$\times$ for
prostate cancer, 2.5$\times$ for breast cancer, and 7.6$\times$ for
mesothelioma: cancers that enter through organism-level channels
(endocrine, tissue architecture) rather than the standard
growth-escape gateway. These tumors severed higher-level coupling
first while leaving cell-level growth control partially intact,
consistent with multiple entry points into the escalation chain.
Their lower mortality (34.8\% vs.\ 42.6\% for all multi-channel
patients) is predicted: they have not yet escaped the most
fundamental coupling layer.

This has a therapeutic implication. If these tumors entered through
the endocrine channel, the severance hierarchy predicts their most
likely next escape: the cell-intrinsic gateway (CellCycle or
PI3K/Growth). Cross-channel dual therapy, endocrine blockade plus
cell-cycle inhibition, targets both the entry channel and the
predicted escape route. This is precisely the rationale behind
CDK4/6 inhibitors (palbociclib, ribociclib) combined with endocrine
therapy in ER+ breast cancer, currently the standard of care and one
of the largest recent advances in breast oncology. The same logic
applies to castration-resistant prostate cancer, where the
PI3K/AKT axis is the most common escape route under androgen
deprivation. The framework does not discover these combinations; it
explains why they work and predicts where the same principle applies
next.

\textbf{The grouping must be biological, not statistical.} A second
objection is that any gene grouping would produce a survival signal:
pick genes, cluster them, count clusters, and the count will predict
something. We tested this directly. Using hierarchical clustering on
Jaccard co-mutation distances across the 92 channel genes with
sufficient mutation frequency ($n \geq 100$), we derived data-driven
gene groupings at every granularity from $k = 2$ to $k = 10$ and
tested each against survival.

The data-driven groupings fail. At $k = 6$, the data-driven cluster
count produces HR~$= 0.80$ ($p = 9 \times 10^{-6}$): more clusters
hit predicts \emph{better} survival, the wrong direction. The
hand-picked biological channels at $k = 6$ produce HR~$= 1.10$
($p = 3 \times 10^{-9}$). The adjusted Rand index between
data-driven and hand-picked groupings is 0.018, effectively zero
overlap.

Co-mutation patterns group genes by which tumors they appear in
(driven by panel coverage, cancer type, and mutational processes),
not by organizational function. The biological channel mapping
captures something that statistical co-occurrence does not: which
organizational system a gene serves. Not just any grouping works.
The grouping must reflect the coupling architecture.

\textbf{Pathogenic variant restriction.} The baseline analysis
counts any non-silent mutation as a severance event, including
variants of unknown significance (VUS). To test whether VUS inflate
the signal, we repeated the analysis under two stricter filters:
truncating mutations only (nonsense, frameshift, splice site) and
truncating plus hotspot missense (recurrent positions with $\geq 5$
patients, capturing KRAS~G12, BRAF~V600, PIK3CA~H1047,
TP53~hotspots, etc.). The signal strengthens: channel-count
HR rises from 1.15 (all non-silent) to 1.16 (truncating only) to
1.19 (truncating + hotspot; $p = 1 \times 10^{-55}$). Mutation
count becomes more protective under stricter filtering (HR~$= 0.75$
vs.\ 0.83 baseline). Removing VUS concentrates the signal; it does
not create it. The severance hierarchy is preserved under
truncating-only filtering: PI3K/Growth and Cell Cycle dominate at
one channel, Endocrine and Immune remain late additions.

\textbf{Limitations.} The analysis does not distinguish hub from
leaf mutations within a channel, nor does it adjust for stage or
treatment. The optimal channel count is an empirical question that
finer-grained pathway databases could resolve. Nevertheless, the
core result is robust across three independent datasets, eight
granularities, within individual cancer types, after controlling for
275 clinical covariates, under three mutation-filtering stringencies,
and against data-driven alternatives: counting organizational systems
disrupted predicts survival better than counting disruptions.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{What Else the Channel Framework Predicts}
\label{sec:predictions-overview}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

Channel count outpredicts mutation count. This is one instance of a
broader principle. If cancer prognosis
is determined by which organizational systems the tumor has escaped,
then the same logic generates predictions about cancer type,
treatment response, and disease progression.

\textbf{1. The cancer subtype depends on which channel breaks, not
which gene mutates.} Disrupting the immune surveillance channel
(transplant immunosuppression, HIV) produces lymphomas and Kaposi
sarcoma, not breast or prostate cancer. Disrupting metabolic
coupling (obesity, diabetes) produces endometrial, liver, and
pancreatic cancers. Disrupting tissue architecture (foreign body
implants, chronic inflammation) produces sarcomas and
site-specific carcinomas. Different channel, different cancer.
Same tissue, different channel, different subtype
(Table~\ref{tab:channels}).

\textbf{2. Graph position within a channel determines severity.}
Not all mutations in the same pathway are equal. A mutation at the
hub of a signaling network (high connectivity, many downstream
targets) severs the channel completely. A mutation at a branch
point leaves alternative routes. A mutation at a leaf node may not
produce cancer at all without additional hits. Example: \emph{BRCA1}
(hub) produces triple-negative breast cancer; \emph{BRCA2}
(downstream) produces HR+ breast cancer. Same pathway, different
graph position, different phenotype (Table~\ref{tab:graph-position}).

\textbf{3. Cross-channel carcinogen exposure is superadditive.}
Two carcinogens hitting different channels should produce
multiplicative risk; two hitting the same channel should produce
additive risk. Smoking (tissue architecture) plus alcohol (direct
genotoxin) produces super-multiplicative head-and-neck cancer risk
(RR\,$\approx$\,35). Same-pathway PAH mixtures produce additive
risk. The interaction type is predictable from the channel
assignment (Table~\ref{tab:carcinogen-interactions}).

\textbf{4. Therapy works when it targets the right channel.}
Hormone therapy should help most when the endocrine channel is
load-bearing and few other channels are severed. Immunotherapy
should help most when the immune channel is intact and being
exploited. Combination therapy should
target \emph{different} channels, not the same channel twice
(Section~\ref{sec:stratification}).

\textbf{5. Cancer progression is unidirectional.} Once a channel
is severed, the tumor descends through the signaling graph toward
more complete decoupling. Targeted therapy accelerates this: ER+
breast cancer under endocrine therapy evolves to triple-negative.
The sequence is predictable from the graph structure
(Section~\ref{sec:directionality}).

\textbf{6. Comorbidities predict cancer subtypes.} Any chronic
disease that degrades a specific channel should increase the rate
of cancers where that channel is load-bearing. HIV increases
immune-surveilled cancers. Diabetes increases metabolically coupled
cancers. The framework unifies dozens of comorbidity--cancer
associations under one principle
(Table~\ref{tab:comorbidity}).

These predictions are testable against existing data. Several are
already confirmed by published findings that were not previously
unified.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{The Genome as Linear Projection of the Signaling Graph}
\label{sec:graph-position}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

The six coupling channels from Section~\ref{sec:empirical} are not
linear pathways. They are graph-structured signaling networks:
directed graphs with hub nodes, branch points, and leaf nodes. The
genome encodes these networks in a linear sequence. This linearity
is a storage format, not a structural description. The network
topology, which nodes connect to which, the branching factor at
each node, the connectivity of each gene product, is the causally
relevant structure.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{The graph-level position of a mutation within a coupling
channel's signaling network determines the degree of channel
severance, the residual coupling architecture, the escape
trajectory, and the cancer phenotype.}
\end{quote}

\noindent Three classes of mutation position produce distinct
predictions (Table~\ref{tab:graph-position}).


\textbf{Example: homologous recombination repair.} The HR pathway
is a graph with identifiable hub, branch, and leaf positions.
\emph{BRCA1} is upstream: it participates in damage recognition,
checkpoint activation, and repair initiation. It connects to many
downstream nodes. Mutation at \emph{BRCA1} severs the DDR channel
completely, producing triple-negative breast cancer (visceral-tropic,
endocrine-independent, aggressive). \emph{BRCA2} is downstream: it
loads RAD51 onto DNA, a specific effector step. Mutation at
\emph{BRCA2} severs a branch, not the whole channel. Residual HR
function persists through BRCA1-mediated signaling. The result is
HR+ breast cancer (bone-tropic, endocrine-dependent, less
aggressive). \emph{RAD51C}, a paralog that assists RAD51 loading,
occupies a similar graph position to \emph{BRCA2} and produces a
similar phenotype. \emph{RAD51A}, the core recombinase and final
effector, is a hub for HR output: its loss eliminates the pathway's
function regardless of upstream status, predicting BRCA1-like
behavior.

\textbf{Generalization.} The same logic applies to every signaling
network:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{RAS pathway:} \emph{KRAS} (hub) mutations produce
   more aggressive cancers than \emph{BRAF} (downstream) mutations
   in the same tissue. This is observed empirically and unexplained
   by mutation-identity accounts.
\item \textbf{Wnt pathway:} \emph{APC} (hub, gatekeeper) loss
   produces more complete pathway activation than downstream
   $\beta$-catenin mutations. APC is the canonical initiating event
   in colorectal cancer.
\item \textbf{PI3K pathway:} \emph{PIK3CA} (hub) mutations should
   produce more severe phenotypes than \emph{AKT} or \emph{mTOR}
   (downstream) mutations in matched tissue.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Why this matters for trial design.} Current oncology
groups mutations by pathway membership: ``HRR-mutant,''
``PI3K-pathway-mutant,'' ``RAS-mutant.'' This grouping conflates
hub and leaf mutations with fundamentally different coupling
architectures. Trials should stratify by graph position within the
pathway, not by pathway membership alone. The topology needed for
this stratification is already mapped in existing pathway databases
(KEGG, Reactome, STRING). The data exists. The stratification
variable has not been applied.

\textbf{Therapeutic efficacy flows down the graph, not up.}
A treatment that restores function at a hub node restores the
entire downstream subgraph. It will therefore work for leaf
mutations in the same pathway, because the leaf is contained within
the hub's downstream network. The converse is not true: a treatment
that compensates for a leaf-node defect addresses only that branch
and will not rescue a hub mutation, where many branches are
simultaneously severed. In the HR pathway: PARP inhibitors work for
\emph{BRCA1} (hub) and also work for \emph{BRCA2} and \emph{RAD51C}
(downstream). A treatment that specifically restores RAD51
loading (the \emph{BRCA2}/\emph{RAD51C} defect) would not rescue a
\emph{BRCA1} mutation, because \emph{BRCA1} severance affects the
entire pathway. This asymmetry is testable across every pathway:
treatments validated at the hub should show efficacy at the leaves;
treatments validated at the leaves should fail at the hub.

\textbf{Branching and tumor heterogeneity.} For branch-point
mutations, the escape trajectory is not deterministic. Multiple
downstream branches survive, and different cells within the same
tumor may take different branches. This produces intratumor
heterogeneity proportional to the branching factor at the mutated
node. Hub mutations produce low heterogeneity (one destination).
Branch-point mutations produce high heterogeneity (multiple
destinations). Leaf mutations produce minimal phenotypic change.
The branching factor is readable from the graph topology, making
the expected heterogeneity predictable before biopsy.

\textbf{Implication for prophylactic combination therapy.} For
branch-point mutations with $b$ surviving branches, the escape set
contains at most $b$ candidates. All $b$ can be enumerated from the
graph topology. Prophylactic blockade requires at most $b$ agents,
each targeting one candidate escape route. The combination is
determined by the graph, not by empirical trial and error.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Formal Framework}
\label{sec:framework}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

The empirical results of Section~\ref{sec:empirical} imply that
cancer prognosis is determined by the number of independent
organizational systems a tumor has escaped, not by the number of
molecular events. This requires three structural properties of
biological organization. Each is stated below in biological terms;
the formal derivations from information-theoretic first principles
appear in \cite{McCarthy2026a, McCarthy2026b, McCarthy2026c,
McCarthy2026d}.

\textbf{Premise 1: Bounded active context ($C_n$).}
Any information-processing entity (cell, tissue, organism) has a
hard limit on the number of regulatory states it can simultaneously
maintain for active inference. A cell can monitor a finite number of
signaling pathways concurrently. An organism's working memory holds
$4 \pm 1$ items \cite{Cowan2001}. We denote this limit $C_n$.

\textbf{Premise 2: Retention under displacement.}
When $C_n$ is full and new information arrives, something must be
displaced. Under survival pressure, the retention criterion is
asymmetric \cite{McCarthy2026c}: retain a regulatory state when its
survival benefit is uncertain; displace it only when a new state
offers strictly higher marginal survival value. The cost of losing a
survival-relevant state (death) vastly exceeds the cost of retaining
a useless one (a wasted context slot). This drives displacement
toward the highest-value regulatory states available to the entity.

\textbf{Premise 3: Adaptive descent.}
An entity with $\gamma > 0$ (nonzero probability of engaging its
adaptive mechanism in response to signals) and $\eta_M > 0$
(positive learning efficiency) reduces its uncertainty about
survival-relevant states over time \cite{McCarthy2026d}. The entity
performs local descent on uncertainty: each adaptive response, on
average, improves its model of the world. This is not an assumption
about intelligence; it is a minimal condition for persistence. Entities
with $\gamma = 0$ (no adaptive response) or $\eta_M = 0$ (no
learning) are eliminated under positive novelty rate
\cite{McCarthy2026d}.

These premises are substrate-independent: they apply to any
information-processing entity satisfying bounded context, not only
to specific tissue types. The tissue-invariance of the resulting
predictions is therefore a consequence of the framework, not an
additional assumption, but it means the framework predicts
\emph{structural} convergence (all severed cells face the same
constraint ceiling) without predicting tissue-specific rates or
molecular details. Section~\ref{sec:predictions} addresses
tissue-specific variation through coupling-channel multiplicity.

Multi-level biological organization follows from these premises.
A cell ($k = 0$), tissue ($k = 1$), organ ($k = 2$), and organism
($k = 3$) form a hierarchy of coupled entities. Each level has its
own bounded context $C_n^{(k)}$, knowledge base, action space, and
sensing function \cite{McCarthy2026a}.

\textbf{Escalation chains.}
When a cell encounters a state exceeding its local capacity, it
escalates to the tissue level; when tissue-level capacity is exceeded,
escalation continues to the organ and organism levels
\cite{McCarthy2026b}. Higher levels engage only when lower levels
fail, achieving $O(1)$ steady-state context cost.

\textbf{Effective context extension.}
Through intact coupling, a cell's effective bounded context exceeds its
intrinsic limit: the cell borrows context from higher organizational
levels via intercellular signaling. A liver cell does not need to
independently represent the organism's metabolic state; it receives
that information via hormonal and neural signaling. The coupling
strength $\lambda_j \in [0,1]$ at each level decomposes into
per-channel components
(Section~\ref{sec:coupling-biology}).

\textbf{Chain severance.}
When coupling is lost ($\lambda \to 0$), the cell's effective context
collapses to its intrinsic cell-level bound. The cell can no longer
borrow context from tissue, organ, or organism levels.

\subsection{Biological Instantiation of the Coupling Coefficients}
\label{sec:coupling-biology}

The abstract coupling coefficients $\lambda_j$ correspond to
specific, measurable intercellular communication mechanisms at each
level of the hierarchy.

\textbf{Level $0 \to 1$ (cell $\to$ tissue coupling).}
This is the primary coupling layer and the level at which most
cancers sever. The coupling mechanisms are:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Gap junctions} (connexins, especially Cx43): direct
   cytoplasmic channels between adjacent cells that share ions,
   metabolites, and second messengers. Gap junctional intercellular
   communication (GJIC) is the highest-bandwidth cell-tissue coupling
   channel. Connexin-43 downregulation is among the earliest events
   in many epithelial cancers \cite{Aasen2016}.
\item \textbf{E-cadherin} (CDH1): homophilic adhesion molecule that
   mediates contact inhibition of proliferation. Loss of E-cadherin
   is the defining event of epithelial-mesenchymal transition (EMT)
   and directly severs the contact-dependent component of $\lambda_1$
   \cite{Hanahan2011}.
\item \textbf{Juxtacrine signaling} (Notch--Delta): direct
   cell-cell contact signaling that maintains tissue identity and
   differentiation state. Requires physical adjacency, destroyed
   by loss of tissue architecture.
\item \textbf{Integrin--ECM attachment}: anchorage to the
   extracellular matrix and basement membrane. Loss of anchorage
   dependence (anoikis resistance) severs the structural component
   of tissue coupling.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Level $1 \to 2$ (tissue $\to$ organ coupling).}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Paracrine signaling}: local growth factors and
   morphogen gradients (Wnt, Hedgehog, BMP, TGF-$\beta$) that
   coordinate tissue-level organization within the organ context.
\item \textbf{Extracellular matrix architecture}: the structural
   scaffold that encodes tissue-level spatial organization and
   transmits mechanical signals.
\item \textbf{Local vasculature}: nutrient and oxygen delivery
   that ties tissue metabolism to organ-level regulation. Vascular
   normalization restores this coupling channel.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Level $2 \to 3$ (organ $\to$ organism coupling).}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Endocrine signaling}: systemic hormones (insulin,
   estrogen, cortisol, thyroid hormone) that couple organ function
   to organismal state. Hormone-dependent cancers (breast, prostate)
   retain partial $\lambda_3$ coupling, explaining their relative
   treatability.
\item \textbf{Immune surveillance}: T-cells, NK cells, and
   macrophages that enforce organism-level quality control on
   aberrant cells. Immune checkpoint molecules (PD-L1, CTLA-4) are
   the molecular implementation of this coupling channel.
\item \textbf{Neural innervation}: autonomic nervous system
   regulation of organ function and tissue homeostasis.
\item \textbf{Circadian regulation}: organism-level temporal
   coordination via the SCN-driven hormonal cascade.
\end{itemize}

More precisely, each aggregate $\lambda_j$ decomposes into per-channel
components. Chain severance can be partial: a cell may lose
gap junctional coupling ($\lambda_1^{\mathrm{GJIC}} \to 0$) while
retaining cadherin-mediated contact inhibition
($\lambda_1^{\mathrm{CDH1}} > 0$). This partial severance produces
the intermediate phenotypes observed in pre-malignant lesions.
Complete severance across all channels at a given level produces the
full malignant phenotype.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Main Result}
\label{sec:main}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

If bounded context, escalation, and knowledge-action inseparability
hold, then chain severance produces convergent malignancy through
four mechanisms. Each is a prediction of the framework; the formal
proofs appear in Papers~1--4.

\textbf{Context collapse.}
Before severance, the cell maintains propositions referencing
tissue-level and organism-level states: differentiation signals,
growth factor dependencies, contact inhibition cues. After severance,
these propositions lose their grounding; they reference states the
cell can no longer observe. By graph necessity \cite{McCarthy2026a},
ungrounded propositions are pruned. The cell's knowledge base
contracts to cell-level observables: local nutrient concentration,
immediate mechanical environment, intracellular state.

\textbf{Action space contraction.}
By knowledge-action inseparability \cite{McCarthy2026c}, as the
knowledge base contracts, the action space contracts with it. Actions
requiring tissue-level coordination (contact inhibition, apoptosis on
organismal command, differentiated quiescence) become inaccessible.
What remains are actions executable with cell-level knowledge alone:
proliferation, metabolic autonomy, motility, immune evasion.

The Warburg effect illustrates this. Cancer cells use aerobic
glycolysis even when oxygen is present, not because oxygen is
unavailable, but because after severance the cell lacks tissue-level
information about oxygen supply reliability and defaults to the
metabolic strategy that requires no such information
\cite{Warburg1956}.

\textbf{Terminal optimization.}
In the intact organism, problems exceeding cell-level capacity
escalate to the tissue level. After severance, there is no higher
level. By escalation convergence \cite{McCarthy2026b}, all
optimization pressure concentrates at the cell. The cell becomes an
autonomous entity optimizing for its own persistence under cell-level
bounded context; the same optimization regime as a unicellular
organism. The cell has not reverted to a unicellular program. It has
been forced into the same optimization regime by the loss of its
escalation chain.

\textbf{Cross-type convergence.}
Cell-level bounded context is small relative to the full repertoire
of cell-level actions. Under the asymmetric retention criterion
\cite{McCarthy2026c}, tissue-specific propositions (zero marginal
value after severance) are displaced by cell-level survival actions
(nonzero value regardless of tissue of origin). The displacement
operates in the same direction for all severed cells. This accounts
for why Hanahan and Weinberg's hallmarks \cite{Hanahan2011} are
observed across cancer types: they are the convergent action space
selected by the retention criterion under cell-level bounded context.

Convergence is not perfect. Residual tissue-specific content produces
tissue-specific variation, especially early in progression. But the
attractor is the same action set, constrained by cell biology, not
by tissue of origin.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Corollaries}
\label{sec:corollaries}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

\textbf{Velocity of malignant transformation.}
\label{cor:velocity}
Malignant transformation does not require the accumulation of a
specific set of mutations. It requires chain severance. A single event
that decouples the cell from tissue-level signaling simultaneously
releases all hallmark behaviors, because all are cell-level actions
suppressed by tissue-level coordination, not absent from the cell's
intrinsic repertoire.

The graph-position result (Section~\ref{sec:graph-position})
sharpens this. A hub mutation severs the channel completely in a
single event. A leaf mutation severs only a branch; additional
mutations are needed to sever the channel. The ``multi-hit''
appearance is not independent capability acquisition but
progressive graph-level descent: each hit severs a deeper node.
Hub mutations produce rapid progression. Leaf mutations produce
the slow, multi-step pattern that the somatic mutation theory
treats as the general case. Both are instances of the same
structural process at different graph positions.
\medskip

\textbf{Therapeutic resistance.}
\label{cor:resistance}
Established tumors exhibit persistent therapeutic resistance because
the severed cell is locally optimal: it is an autonomous optimizer
that learns from therapeutic pressure \cite{McCarthy2026d}.
Resistance is the norm because therapy changes the optimization
landscape without changing the optimization regime.

The graph-position result (Section~\ref{sec:graph-position}) adds
a prediction: resistance trajectory follows the graph. A therapy
targeting a leaf node is evaded by routing through an adjacent
branch. A therapy targeting a hub node has fewer escape routes.
Effective therapy must either restore the chain (re-establish
$C_n^{\mathrm{eff}} > C_n^{(0)}$) or target actions that are
necessary under $C_n^{(0)}$ regardless of graph position.
\medskip

\textbf{The atavistic pattern without atavistic causation.}
\label{cor:atavistic}
The phylostratigraphic signal (cancer genes being disproportionately
ancient \cite{Trigos2017}) is real but does not imply atavistic
reversion. Ancient genes are precisely the genes optimized for
cell-level bounded context during the unicellular era. After chain
severance, the same constraint selects for the same solutions.
The genes are not activated because they are ancient. They are
activated because they encode cell-level actions, and they happen to
be ancient because unicellular organisms faced the same constraint.

The graph-position result (Section~\ref{sec:graph-position})
adds a structural prediction. Hub genes in conserved signaling
networks tend to be ancient (they are the most constrained nodes).
Hub mutations produce the most complete severance and the strongest
atavistic signal. Leaf mutations produce partial severance and a
weaker signal. The atavistic theory predicts the ancient gene set
activates as a unit. This framework predicts activation proportional
to severance degree, which is determined by graph position.
\medskip

\textbf{Metastasis as optimal foraging.}
\label{cor:metastasis}
Metastasis is not an acquired capability but the default exploratory
behavior of an autonomous entity optimizing under bounded context in a
spatially heterogeneous environment. After chain severance, the cell
has no spatial constraint beyond its local environment. By the descent
result of \cite{McCarthy2026d}, the cell performs local descent on
uncertainty, discovering that movement to nutrient-rich regions reduces
uncertainty about survival.

\textbf{Inefficiency is predicted, not anomalous.} Metastasis is
exploration under $C_n^{(0)}$: cell-level bounded context with no
tissue-level guidance. More than 99.9\% of circulating tumor cells
die without colonizing a distant site \cite{Massague2016}. This
massive inefficiency is exactly what the framework predicts:
exploration without higher-level coordination is high-variance.
The cell has $\gamma > 0$ (it engages adaptive mechanisms) but
its context window is too small to model the circulatory environment,
immune surveillance, or distant-site compatibility. Each step is
locally optimal (movement reduces local uncertainty) but the
cell lacks the $C_n^{\mathrm{eff}}$ to plan a viable multi-step
trajectory. The rare successful metastases are not evidence of
acquired capability but survivorship bias over massive parallel
exploration.

The ``invasion-metastasis cascade'' is not a sequence of
independently acquired capabilities. It is cell-level exploration
in a spatially structured environment. The graph-position result
(Section~\ref{sec:graph-position}) adds a prediction for metastatic
tropism: the remaining coupling architecture determines which
distant sites are compatible. Bone-tropic metastasis requires
endocrine coupling (the osteoblast niche is endocrine-dependent).
Visceral-tropic metastasis does not. The tropism is readable from
the coupling architecture, not from the primary mutation alone.
\medskip

\textbf{Transplant rejection as chain mismatch.}
\label{cor:transplant}
Organ transplant rejection is not chain severance but chain
mismatch: the transplanted tissue has intact internal coupling
(cell to tissue) but mismatched organism-level coupling. The immune
system's rejection response is the escalation chain functioning
correctly, detecting cells whose coupling markers do not match
the recipient organism.

A transplanted organ retains its internal tissue organization: the
cells are coupled to each other and to tissue-level architecture
via gap junctions, cadherins, and paracrine signaling. The
$\lambda_1$ coupling channels are intact. What is mismatched is
$\lambda_3^{\mathrm{immune}}$: the organism-level immune
surveillance system recognizes the transplanted cells' MHC markers
as foreign, not coupled to \emph{this} organism's escalation
chain.

At the level of the coupling variable $\lambda_3^{\mathrm{immune}}$,
chain severance (cancer) and chain mismatch (transplant) produce the
same signal: absent or aberrant organism-level coupling. The immune
mechanisms differ in detail; transplant rejection is driven by MHC
mismatch recognition, while cancer immune evasion involves PD-L1
upregulation and MHC-I downregulation. But structurally, both
represent failures of the level $2 \to 3$ coupling, and the
organism-level enforcement mechanism responds to both.

Immunosuppressive therapy (cyclosporine, tacrolimus) weakens the
organism-level coupling enforcement
$\lambda_3^{\mathrm{immune}} \to 0$ globally. This permits the
mismatched organ but simultaneously disables the surveillance
mechanism that detects genuine chain severance. The well-documented
2--5$\times$ elevation in cancer incidence among transplant
recipients \cite{Engels2011} is the predicted consequence:
weakened chain enforcement permits both the intended mismatch
\emph{and} unintended severance events.

\textbf{Tolerance induction} -- protocols that establish mixed
hematopoietic chimerism or regulatory T-cell-mediated acceptance
-- operates differently. Rather than weakening enforcement, it
re-establishes matching coupling: the recipient's immune system
learns to recognize the transplanted tissue as part of its own
escalation chain. The coupling
$\lambda_3^{\mathrm{immune}}$ is restored for the transplant
specifically, while global enforcement remains intact. The
framework predicts that tolerance induction should produce better
long-term outcomes than chronic immunosuppression, not only
for graft survival but for overall survival, because it
preserves the organism-level chain enforcement that prevents
cancer. Early clinical evidence from mixed chimerism protocols
is consistent with this prediction \cite{Kawai2008}.

HLA matching reduces the mismatch at the coupling interface itself,
minimizing the signal that triggers enforcement without weakening
enforcement. This is why HLA-matched transplants require less
immunosuppression and have better outcomes: less mismatch means
less enforcement to suppress.

\textbf{Coupling-channel specificity predicts cancer type distribution.}
Immunosuppression weakens $\lambda_3^{\mathrm{immune}}$ specifically,
organism-level immune enforcement, while leaving tissue-level
coupling ($\lambda_1$: gap junctions, contact inhibition, basement
membrane integrity) intact. Immunosuppressed patients should show disproportionately elevated
rates of cancers where immune surveillance is the \emph{primary}
coupling channel, and near-baseline rates of cancers where tissue
architecture provides the dominant restraint.

This is confirmed by the transplant cancer data \cite{Engels2011}.
Cancers dominated by immune-surveillance coupling show massive
elevation: Kaposi sarcoma (${\sim}60\times$), non-Hodgkin lymphoma
(${\sim}7\times$), and non-melanoma skin cancers, all
immune-surveilled or virally mediated. Cancers where tissue
architecture is the primary coupling mechanism show minimal
elevation: breast (${\sim}1.2\times$), prostate (${\sim}0.9\times$),
and colorectal (${\sim}1.2\times$), cancers restrained primarily
by glandular organization, basement membrane, and epithelial
architecture, none of which immunosuppression disrupts.

This pattern is difficult to explain under the somatic mutation
theory (which predicts uniform elevation proportional to reduced
immune clearance of mutant cells) or the atavistic theory (which
has no mechanism for coupling-channel specificity). It follows
directly from the framework: weakening one coupling channel
($\lambda_3^{\mathrm{immune}}$) permits severance only in tissues
where that channel was load-bearing.
\medskip

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Mechanisms of Chain Severance}
\label{sec:mechanisms}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

Chain severance is not a single event but a spectrum of decoupling
mechanisms, each reducing $\lambda_j$ toward zero
(Table~\ref{tab:severance-mechanisms}).


All four mechanisms produce the same outcome: the convergent
phenotype follows regardless of \emph{which} mechanism severed the
chain. This explains why cancers arising from different mechanisms
(hereditary, environmental, sporadic) converge on the same
phenotypic endpoints.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{The Encoding Hierarchy in Cancer}
\label{sec:encoding}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

The encoding hierarchy of \cite{McCarthy2026d} has a specific
consequence for cancer that connects to the empirical phenomenon of
tumor heterogeneity.

In the intact organism, actions at each encoding level have been
validated to the threshold $\theta_i = 1 - \varepsilon / C_i$. The
genomic level ($L_0$) encodes actions validated across evolutionary
timescales. The epigenetic level ($L_1$) encodes tissue-specific
programs validated across developmental timescales. The active
context level ($L_n$) encodes moment-to-moment responses.

After chain severance, the encoding hierarchy is disrupted at all
levels above the cell:

\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Organism-level encodings} (hormonal responses,
   circadian regulation, immune cooperation) lose their validation
   context. They were validated under $C_n^{\mathrm{eff}}$; they are
   now evaluated under $C_n^{(0)}$. Many fail the retention criterion.

\item \textbf{Tissue-level encodings} (differentiation state,
   contact inhibition, growth factor dependence) similarly lose
   validation context.

\item \textbf{Cell-level encodings} (basic metabolism, division
   machinery, DNA repair) retain their validation. They were
   validated under $C_n^{(0)}$ originally and remain valid.
\end{itemize}

The result is \emph{selective devalidation}: the encoding hierarchy
does not collapse uniformly but selectively loses its higher-level
content. What remains is a cell operating on cell-level encodings,
the same encodings that a unicellular organism would maintain. This
is the encoding-level explanation for the atavistic gene expression
pattern observed by Trigos et al.\ \cite{Trigos2017}: ancient genes
are preferentially retained not because they are ``reactivated'' but
because they are the ones whose validation survives context collapse.

\textbf{Tumor heterogeneity.} The graph-position result
(Section~\ref{sec:graph-position}) predicts heterogeneity from
topology: hub mutations produce low heterogeneity (one destination),
branch-point mutations produce high heterogeneity (multiple
surviving branches), and leaf mutations produce minimal change.
Clonal evolution \cite{Nowell1976} describes the dynamics; the
graph provides the direction.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Engagement with Prior Work}
\label{sec:prior}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

Table~\ref{tab:prior-work} summarizes the relationship between
existing cancer frameworks and chain severance.


The closest existing framework is TOFT \cite{Sonnenschein2000}.
It correctly identifies the organizational level (tissue, not cell)
and the default proliferative state. Our framework provides the
formalism TOFT has lacked: the escalation chain is the formal
structure of tissue organization, $C_n^{\mathrm{eff}}$ is the
measure of organizational integration, and chain severance is
the formal description of organizational breakdown. TOFT's
``default proliferative state'' is our ``necessary action space
under cell-level $C_n$.''

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{The Central Prediction: Coupling-Channel Specificity}
\label{sec:predictions}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

The framework's unique predictive signature is \textbf{coupling-channel
specificity}: the cancer type that emerges from any disruption is
determined by \emph{which coupling channel} $\lambda_j$ was
load-bearing for that tissue. This is the one prediction that
distinguishes the chain-severance framework from all existing cancer
theories. The somatic mutation theory predicts cancer incidence based on
proliferation rate and mutational exposure. The atavistic theory
predicts a uniform reversion to unicellular programs. Neither has a
mechanism for predicting which cancer type emerges from which
disruption. The chain-severance framework does: sever a specific
channel, and the cancers that appear are those where that channel was
the primary organizational restraint.

\subsection{Channel-specific natural experiments}

Five classes of natural experiment test this principle, each disrupting
a different coupling channel and producing a different cancer type
distribution (Table~\ref{tab:channels}).


\subsection{Carcinogen classification by coupling channel}

The principle extends to carcinogenesis. Two carcinogens hitting the
same tissue but damaging different coupling channels should produce
different cancer subtypes. Lung cancer provides the clearest test.
Smoking causes chronic inflammation and epithelial remodeling, damage
to $\lambda_1$ (tissue architecture), and is associated primarily
with squamous cell carcinoma and adenocarcinoma. Radon causes direct
cell-level DNA damage via alpha particles and is associated primarily
with small cell lung cancer: poorly differentiated, neuroendocrine,
maximally aggressive. Different channel, different subtype, same
organ.

Carcinogen classification should
specify which coupling channel the carcinogen disrupts, not merely
which tissue is exposed, because the disrupted channel determines
the cancer subtype. Re-analyzing existing
epidemiological datasets that record both exposure type and cancer
subtype within the same organ would test this directly.

\subsection{Comorbidity as coupling-channel degradation}

The coupling-channel principle extends beyond exogenous carcinogens
to endogenous disease. Any disease that chronically degrades a
specific coupling channel~$\lambda_j$ should increase the rate of
cancers where $\lambda_j$ is load-bearing, and should increase the
\emph{specific subtype} associated with that channel, not merely
cancer incidence in general. Table~\ref{tab:comorbidity} compiles
six well-established comorbidity associations, each currently treated
as a separate finding in a separate literature. The framework unifies
them under a single principle.


Knowing which
coupling channel a disease degrades predicts which cancer subtypes
will increase in that patient population. Cross-referencing disease-specific cohorts (e.g., diabetes registries,
autoimmune disease registries) with cancer subtype incidence, stratified
by coupling-channel assignment, would test this. Existing comorbidity databases are
sufficient; the framework provides the organizing variable that is
currently missing.

Diseases that \emph{strengthen}
a coupling channel should be protective against the corresponding
cancer subtypes. Autoimmune conditions, characterized by
\emph{overactive} immune coupling, should protect against cancers
where immune surveillance is the load-bearing channel, while
potentially increasing risk for cancers driven by chronic
inflammatory tissue damage. This bidirectional prediction
distinguishes the framework from generic ``inflammation causes
cancer'' accounts, which predict only increased risk.

\subsection{Specific predictions}

The framework generates eight falsifiable predictions.
Table~\ref{tab:predictions} summarizes six that follow directly
from the results above.


\textbf{Prediction 7: Cross-channel carcinogen exposure is
superadditive; same-channel is additive.} Different channels
($\lambda_i \perp \lambda_j$) produce multiplicative risk;
same channel produces additive risk; partial overlap produces
sub-multiplicative risk. Table~\ref{tab:carcinogen-interactions}
confirms this gradient across eight agent pairs.


The Armitage--Doll multistage model \cite{Armitage1954} captures
the same structure but does not identify what the ``stages'' are.
The coupling-channel framework provides the identification: stages
are coupling channels. For any carcinogen pair whose interaction
is unknown, the framework predicts the interaction type from the
channel assignment \emph{before} the data are collected.

\textbf{Prediction 8: Sequential monotherapy produces predictable
subtype transitions.} The order of therapy determines the order of
channel severance. In ER+ breast cancer: endocrine therapy $\to$
ER loss $\to$ HER2-targeting $\to$ HER2 loss $\to$ triple-negative.
The same therapeutic sequence should produce the same subtype
transitions across patients. Sequential monotherapy is a controlled
demolition of the escalation chain, one channel at a time.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Directionality of Cancer Progression}
\label{sec:directionality}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

\textbf{Progression is unidirectional,
from more coupled to less coupled.}

\subsection{The downward ratchet}

In graph terms (Section~\ref{sec:graph-position}), progression is
descent through the signaling graph. Each severed node removes
constraints that were supporting downstream nodes. A hub mutation
severs the channel in one step. A branch-point mutation leaves
surviving branches, but each branch is now exposed: severing it
requires fewer additional hits because the upstream support is gone.
The ratchet is graph descent under selection pressure, and it moves
in one direction: toward more complete severance.

Targeted therapy accelerates the ratchet. Therapy targeting a
specific coupling channel creates selection pressure to sever
\emph{that specific channel}. The cancer evolves to eliminate
dependence on the targeted channel, producing a more decoupled
phenotype.

Three clinical phenomena confirm this:
ER+ breast cancer under endocrine therapy $\to$ triple-negative.
Prostate adenocarcinoma under androgen deprivation $\to$
neuroendocrine small cell. EGFR+ lung adenocarcinoma under EGFR
inhibition $\to$ small cell lung cancer. In each case the cancer
severs the channel that therapy is pressuring. The clinical term is
\emph{lineage plasticity}. The structural explanation is graph
descent: the cell moves to the next viable node below the one
being targeted.

\subsection{Why upward progression does not occur}

Graph descent is irreversible without external intervention.
Re-coupling requires signals the cell no longer receives and
propositions the retention criterion has already displaced. The
cell cannot bootstrap back up the graph. It would need the
information it has already lost. Differentiation therapy works
by \emph{externally providing} those signals, restoring
$\lambda_j$ from outside the cell.

\subsection{Therapeutic implication: single-channel targeting is
self-defeating}

Therapy targeting a single coupling channel accelerates severance
of that channel. The cell optimizes away from dependence on any
channel under therapeutic pressure. Sequential monotherapy drives
the cancer down the graph one channel at a time.
Section~\ref{sec:therapy} develops the therapeutic consequences:
cross-channel combinations, chain restoration, and the hybrid
strategy.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Classification of Therapies by Chain Restoration}
\label{sec:therapy}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

Cancer therapies fall into three categories based on their structural relationship to the escalation
chain. The category predicts durability of response.

\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Remove the decoupling cause.} Eliminate the agent that
   is actively degrading coupling channels, before the ratchet
   completes. Works by halting the severance process, allowing
   intact coupling to reassert itself.
\item \textbf{Restore coupling from outside.} Externally re-establish
   the coupling channel that has been severed, returning
   tissue-level actions to the cell's accessible action space.
   Works even after severance because it provides the signals
   and propositions that $K_0$ has lost.
\item \textbf{Impose selection pressure on a decoupled optimizer.}
   Attack or constrain a cell that is already optimizing under
   cell-level $C_n^{(0)}$. The cell's $\gamma > 0$ and
   $\eta_M > 0$ imply continued adaptation; resistance is structurally
   predicted.
\end{enumerate}

\noindent The critical distinction is between \emph{targeting a
coupling channel} (which accelerates severance, the
self-defeating prediction of Section~\ref{sec:directionality})
and \emph{removing whatever is degrading the coupling channel}
(which halts severance). The same signaling pathway can be
involved in both, but the direction of the intervention is
opposite.

\textbf{Molecular subtypes as coupling-channel subtypes.}
Molecular subtypes (ER+, HER2+, triple-negative) correspond to
which coupling channel was load-bearing. ER+ breast cancer:
$\lambda_3^{\mathrm{endocrine}}$ was the primary restraint.
Triple-negative: tissue-architecture coupling ($\lambda_1$) has
also severed. By the graph-position result
(Section~\ref{sec:graph-position}), the subtype is determined by
where in the signaling graph the mutation sits. The receptor is a
symptom of which channel severed. The channel is the therapeutic
target.

\subsection{Therapy Examples by Category}

Table~\ref{tab:therapy-classification} maps specific therapies to
their structural category and predicted durability.


\textbf{The critical distinction} is between \emph{removing a
decoupling cause} (which halts severance) and \emph{targeting a
coupling channel} (which accelerates it). Imatinib and
anti-estrogen therapy may both target kinase pathways, but the
structural direction is opposite: driver inhibition removes a
decoupling cause; coupling-channel blockade removes a coupling
signal.

\textbf{The timing prediction.} Removing the decoupling cause
works before the ratchet completes but not after. Asbestos
abatement prevents new mesotheliomas but does not shrink
established tumors. Imatinib works because BCR-ABL is the
\emph{ongoing} decoupling cause; in blast crisis (fully
decoupled), response rates drop sharply.

\textbf{Denervation as decoupling-cause removal.}
An apparent counterexample clarifies the taxonomy. Zhao et
al.\ \cite{Zhao2017} showed that vagotomy \emph{suppresses}
gastric tumorigenesis. If neural signaling were a coupling channel,
severing it should increase cancer risk. The resolution: the vagus
nerve in the gastric context carries a proliferative signal
(M3 receptor $\to$ Wnt $\to$ stem cell expansion) that overrides
tissue-level quiescence signals. It is a decoupling cause, not a
coupling channel. Denervation removes the cause, and tissue-level
coupling reasserts. Each signal must be classified by structural
role, coupling or decoupling, not by anatomical origin.

\subsection{The Hybrid Strategy}

The optimal therapeutic strategy combines
chain restoration with exploitation of structural constraints:
\begin{enumerate}
\item Restore coupling where possible (differentiation therapy,
   immunotherapy, microenvironment normalization).
\item For cells where coupling cannot be restored, target actions
   that are \emph{necessary} under cell-level $C_n^{(0)}$, actions
   the cell cannot optimize away from because they are structurally
   required by the bounded-context constraint. The Warburg effect
   (aerobic glycolysis) is a candidate: if glycolytic metabolism is
   \emph{necessary} under cell-level bounded context (because
   oxidative phosphorylation requires tissue-level oxygen delivery
   infrastructure), then targeting glycolysis imposes a constraint
   the cell cannot evolve around.
\item Remove decoupling causes where identifiable (pathogen
   eradication, environmental remediation, oncogenic driver
   inhibition).
\item Use cytoreductive therapies (chemotherapy, radiation)
   only to reduce tumor burden before chain-restoring
   interventions, not as standalone strategies.
\end{enumerate}

\textbf{Clinical evidence.} The relative success of combination
immunotherapy (chain restoration at level $2 \to 3$) over
single-agent chemotherapy (non-restoring) in melanoma, non-small cell
lung cancer, and renal cell carcinoma is consistent with this
prediction. The curative success of ATRA in APL (chain restoration at
level $0 \to 1$) versus the near-universal resistance to
chemotherapy-only regimens in other acute leukemias provides the
strongest existing evidence.

\subsection{Combination Design by Coupling Architecture: The HRR Example}
\label{sec:hrr-combinations}

A concrete prediction for ongoing clinical
trials in homologous recombination repair (HRR)-deficient cancers.
Current trial design groups patients by shared pathway defect:
\emph{BRCA1}, \emph{BRCA2}, \emph{PALB2}, \emph{RAD51C}, and
\emph{RAD51D} mutations are treated as a single cohort (``HRR-mutant'')
under the assumption that the shared DNA damage repair deficiency
determines therapeutic response.

This grouping is wrong.
The shared DDR deficiency identifies which channel was
\emph{damaged}, but combination efficacy depends on which channels
remain \emph{load-bearing} for the tumor. These differ by gene:

\begin{itemize}
\item \emph{BRCA1} mutations produce predominantly triple-negative
   breast cancer, with visceral-tropic metastasis (lung, distant
   lymph nodes; $\sim$70\% visceral) \cite{Song2020}. The endocrine
   coupling channel ($\lambda_3^{\mathrm{endocrine}}$) was never
   load-bearing for these tumors.
\item \emph{BRCA2} mutations produce predominantly HR+ breast
   cancer, with bone-tropic metastasis ($\sim$75\% bone)
   \cite{Song2020}. The endocrine coupling channel is load-bearing.
   Bone-tropic clones depend on the osteoblast niche, which is
   endocrine-coupled, making ESR1 mutation the most likely escape
   route under endocrine therapy.
\item \emph{RAD51C} mutations, like \emph{BRCA2}, are associated
   with HR+ disease. Published cohorts are small, but the coupling
   architecture predicts bone-tropic, endocrine-dependent behavior
   analogous to \emph{BRCA2}.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Prediction for cross-channel combination trials.}
A PARP inhibitor (DDR channel) combined with an oral SERD
(endocrine channel) is a cross-channel combination. The framework
predicts this combination should benefit \emph{BRCA2} and
\emph{RAD51C} patients, where the SERD blocks the most likely
escape route (ESR1 mutation in bone-tropic, endocrine-dependent
disease). It should \emph{not} meaningfully benefit \emph{BRCA1}
patients, where the endocrine channel is not load-bearing and
the SERD targets a channel the tumor does not depend on.

Trials that group all HRR-mutant patients into a single cohort
are averaging across fundamentally different coupling
architectures. The signal from \emph{BRCA2} patients benefiting
from cross-channel endocrine combinations is diluted by
\emph{BRCA1} patients for whom that combination is irrelevant.
If \emph{BRCA1} patients constitute a large fraction of the
cohort, a genuinely effective cross-channel strategy may fail
to reach statistical significance.

This prediction is testable by subgroup analysis of existing
trial data: stratify PARP + SERD combination results by
\emph{BRCA1} versus \emph{BRCA2} and compare response rates.
If the framework is correct, the difference should be substantial.

\textbf{Prophylactic escape-route blockade.} The ratchet
prediction (Section~\ref{sec:directionality}) extends this logic
further. For stage~IV disease where the ratchet is already in
motion, the escape phenotype is predictable from the tissue and
the coupling architecture. For bone-dominant HR+ disease under
endocrine therapy, the predicted escape sequence is:
ER loss (ESR1 mutation) $\to$ potential HER2 amplification $\to$
triple-negative phenotype. Adding agents that block the
\emph{predicted} escape route, not the current phenotype, could
stall the ratchet before the next channel severs. The additional
toxicity is minimal because the agent targets a different channel,
not adding dose to the channel already under therapeutic pressure.

Many destination therapies are already approved for the
destination subtype (e.g., trastuzumab for HER2+ disease,
platinum-based chemotherapy for triple-negative disease). The
barrier to prophylactic use is not drug availability but the
absence of a framework justifying treatment of a phenotype the
tumor has not yet acquired. The coupling-channel framework
provides that justification: the escape is structurally
predicted, and preemptive blockade is structurally motivated.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Stratification by Coupling Architecture, Not Pathway Co-location}
\label{sec:stratification}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

The HRR example of Section~\ref{sec:hrr-combinations} is an
instance of a general problem. Current oncology stratifies patients
by \emph{what broke}: HRR-mutant, PI3K-pathway-mutant, RAS-mutant,
DDR-deficient. These are groupings by the damaged channel. But
combination efficacy, escape trajectory, metastatic tropism, and
therapeutic resistance are determined by the channels that
\emph{remain intact}. Two tumors with the same mutation in the same
pathway can have completely different coupling architectures depending
on tissue of origin, metastatic site, and which other channels are
load-bearing.

\begin{quote}
\textbf{The correct stratification variable for combination therapy
design is not the damaged pathway but the residual coupling
architecture}: which channels remain load-bearing, and which escape
routes are therefore structurally predicted.
\end{quote}

\textbf{Basket trials.} The pattern is visible in existing data.
Basket trials that group patients by shared mutation across tissue
types consistently underperform tissue-specific trials. BRAF~V600E
in melanoma, colorectal cancer, and thyroid cancer shares the same
molecular defect, but vemurafenib produces durable responses in
melanoma and minimal benefit in colorectal cancer. The field calls
this ``tissue context'' but lacks a structural account of why tissue
context determines response. The coupling-channel framework provides
one: the tissue determines which channels are load-bearing, which
determines the escape trajectory, which determines what combinations
work. Same mutation, different coupling architecture, different
outcome.

\textbf{Testable predictions.} This claim generates a family of
easily testable predictions:

\begin{enumerate}
\item For any mutation-defined cohort (e.g., HRR-mutant,
   BRAF-mutant, PIK3CA-mutant), subgroup analysis by tissue of
   origin and metastatic site should reveal statistically
   significant differences in combination therapy response that
   are not predicted by the mutation alone.
\item Cross-channel combinations (agents targeting different
   coupling channels) should outperform same-channel combinations
   (agents targeting the same pathway) across every mutation class,
   when controlled for toxicity.
\item Within a mutation-defined cohort, the \emph{specific}
   cross-channel combination that works should be predictable from
   the tissue's coupling architecture: endocrine-dependent tissues
   benefit from endocrine-channel agents, immune-surveilled tissues
   benefit from immune-channel agents, architecturally coupled
   tissues benefit from microenvironment-restoring agents.
\item Retrospective re-analysis of failed basket trials, stratified
   by residual coupling architecture rather than by mutation, should
   recover efficacy signals in tissue-appropriate subgroups that were
   diluted by the mutation-only grouping.
\end{enumerate}

Trial design should
stratify not only by molecular alteration but by coupling
architecture. The mutation identifies the damaged channel. The
tissue, the metastatic site, and the residual receptor profile
identify the load-bearing channels. Both are needed to predict
which combinations will work and which escape routes to block
prophylactically.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Implications}
\label{sec:implications}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

\textbf{Cancer is not a disease of cells.} It is a disease of
organizational coupling. The cell itself is functioning correctly;
it is optimizing under its bounded context, exactly as the theorems
predict any entity must. The pathology is in the severed escalation
chain, not in the cell.

\textbf{The ``war on cancer'' metaphor is structurally wrong.} Cancer
cells are not invaders to be destroyed; they are former cooperators
who have lost the organizational infrastructure that made cooperation
possible. Killing them (chemotherapy, radiation) treats the symptom.
Restoring the organizational infrastructure (differentiation therapy,
microenvironment normalization, coupling restoration) treats the
cause. The distinction is between fighting an entity and repairing a
relationship.

\textbf{Prevention over cure.} If cancer is chain severance, then
prevention is coupling maintenance. Factors that maintain tissue
organization (anti-inflammatory interventions, microenvironment
homeostasis, gap junction maintenance) should reduce cancer risk
more effectively than factors that reduce mutational burden,
though the two are related, since mutations are one mechanism of
severance.

\textbf{Peto's paradox.} Large organisms do not develop cancer at
rates proportional to cell count \cite{Peto1975}. The framework
explains this: larger organisms have deeper signaling graphs, more
coupling channels, and higher $C_n^{\mathrm{eff}}$. More severance
is required before cell-level optimization dominates. More cells
but also more coupling yields a roughly constant severance rate.

\textbf{Benign tumors and non-progression.} Most dysplastic lesions
never become malignant \cite{Nowell1976}. In graph terms: a leaf
mutation severs only a terminal branch. The rest of the signaling
graph compensates. Partial decoupling ($0 < \lambda_j < 1$) does
not produce full convergence to the cell-level action space.
Progression requires descent past a hub or branch point where
cascading decoupling begins \cite{Folkman1971}.

% ------------------------------------------------------------------
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}
% ------------------------------------------------------------------

Cancer is not random. Cancer is not ancient. Cancer is what happens
when a cell loses its escalation chain.

This paper makes three primary claims. First, coupling-channel
specificity: the cancer type that emerges depends on which channel
was load-bearing. Second, stratification by residual coupling
architecture: combination efficacy depends on the channels that
remain intact, not the channel that broke. Third, graph-position
determines phenotype: a mutation's position in the signaling
graph (hub, branch, leaf) predicts severance degree, escape
trajectory, heterogeneity, and therapeutic response.

Together these claims unify the three major cancer theories.
SMT identifies the mechanisms of chain severance (mutations).
The atavistic theory identifies the phenotypic pattern (convergence
on unicellular-like behavior). TOFT identifies the organizational
level (tissue, not cell). This framework provides the structure:
mutations sever the escalation chain at a specific graph position,
producing a cell that optimizes under cell-level bounded context,
which converges on the same action space that shaped unicellular
life. Not by reversion but by structural necessity.

The contribution is both empirical and structural. The empirical
result (channel count outpredicts mutation count, channels are
severed in escalation order, the signal survives 275 covariates and
three mutation-filtering stringencies) stands independently of the
framework. The structural claims (bounded context, escalation
convergence, knowledge-action inseparability) are what the data
implies about the organization of multicellular life; the formal
proofs appear in
\cite{McCarthy2026a, McCarthy2026b, McCarthy2026c, McCarthy2026d}.
The predictions
(Sections~\ref{sec:predictions}--\ref{sec:stratification}) are
testable against existing data and are offered in that spirit.

