\begin{table}[p]
\centering
\caption{Falsifiable predictions from coupling-channel specificity.}
\label{tab:predictions}
\begin{tabular}{@{}>{\raggedright}p{5cm}>{\raggedright}p{9cm}>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{6cm}@{}}
\toprule
Prediction & Test method & Distinguishes from \\
\midrule
$\lambda_j$ predicts malignancy better than mutational burden
 & Measure intercellular communication alongside mutational profiling
 & SMT (mutation-first) \\[4pt]
Gene expression is constraint-determined, not phylogeny-determined
 & Check if recently evolved cell-level genes are upregulated in cancer
 & Atavistic theory (ancient genes only) \\[4pt]
Differentiation therapy outperforms cytotoxic therapy
 & Compare durability: chain-restoring vs.\ cell-killing therapies
 & SMT (target the mutation) \\[4pt]
Tumor heterogeneity correlates with severance gradient
 & Spatial transcriptomics + communication assays within single tumors
 & Clonal evolution (random drift) \\[4pt]
Necessary vs.\ contingent hallmarks
 & Proliferation and metabolic autonomy in every cancer; angiogenesis and immune evasion vary by channel
 & Hallmarks (all acquired equally) \\[4pt]
Cancer incidence tracks coupling degradation, not mutation accumulation
 & Esophagus: high mutations, robust coupling, low cancer. Pancreas: fragile coupling, high cancer \cite{Martincorena2015}
 & SMT (more mutations = more cancer) \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\end{table}

